The model of discrete character evolution

I’m using this page to explore comparative methods beginning with models of discrete trait evolution. I think one of the best presentations that I’ve seen of this was John Huelsenbeck’s lecture at the Bodega Phylogenetics workshop. He also has a great tutorial available online for the Woods Hole course which is very similar. This post is the result of R markdown document that I have created in an attempt to make sure that I understand all of this. The entire R markdown document is available via github.

When we think about the evolution of discrete characters (either DNA or other traits). We usually think of a continuous time Markov model that describes the probability of changes in our character as it evolves over our phylogeny. At the heart of this type of model is the Q-matrix. This matrix contains transition rates. For illustration we can use a matrix like this which represents the evolution of a binary trait that can have states 0 or 1:

##      0    1
## 0 -0.3  0.3
## 1  0.4 -0.4

On the left of the matrix we have the current state and on the top of the matrix we have the ending state. So in this case the rate of transition from state 0 to state 1 is 0.3 while the rate of transition from state 1 to state 0 is .4. These rates will usually be referred to as q01 and q10 respectively. The diagonal of the matrix is set so each row is equal to 0.

What these rates actually describe is the exponentially distributed expected waiting time till we see a transition in our trait. For instance we could use this formula to calculate the waiting time for a transition from state 0 to state 1. \(t=-\frac{1}{\lambda} log_e(u)\) Where \(u\) is a random number between 0 and 1, and in our example \(\lambda\) will equal .3.

## [1] "We draw a random number = 0.2655086631421"

and so we now can calculate that the next transition in our trait occurs

\(t=-\frac{log_e(.2655)}{0.3}=4.42\)

this equation also lets us calculate the distribution of all possible waiting times that we could see given our Q-matrix.

We can also do the same for transition from q10.

The transition rates in a Q-matrix tell us about the probability of a transition in our trait over very short periods of times but not over longer periods of time where we may have had multiple transitions on a branch for this we must convert our Q-matrix to a probability matrix or P-matrix that is specific to the time period (or branch length) of interest. We could do this my simulating the evolution of our trait using the Q-matrix. For instance lets say we have a branch in our tree that is 1 unit long and we want to know the probability of experiencing transitions between our states given a branch length of 1. The code below will perform this simulation 10000 times to calculate that probability.

initial.st <- c(rep(0,times=5000), rep(1,times=5000))
changes <- final.st <- vector()
total.bl <- 1
for(i in 1:10000){
  current.bl <- 0
  current.st <- initial.st[i]
  changes[i] <- 0
  while(current.bl < total.bl){
    final.st[i] <- current.st
    if(current.st == 0){
      set.seed(i)
      wait.time <- -log(runif(1))/qmat[1,2]
      if((wait.time + current.bl) > total.bl) current.bl <- total.bl 
      if((wait.time + current.bl) < total.bl){
        current.bl <- current.bl + wait.time
        current.st <- 1
        changes[i] <- changes[i] + 1
        final.st[i] <- current.st
      } 
    }
    if(current.st == 1){
      wait.time <- -log(runif(1))/qmat[2,1]
      if((wait.time + current.bl) > total.bl) current.bl <- total.bl 
      if((wait.time + current.bl) < total.bl){
        current.bl <- current.bl + wait.time
        current.st <- 0
        changes[i] <- changes[i] + 1
        final.st[i] <- current.st
      }
    }
  }
}
pmat <- matrix(c(sum(final.st[1:5000]==0)/5000,
                 sum(final.st[5001:10000]==0)/5000,
                 sum(final.st[1:5000]==1)/5000,
                 sum(final.st[5001:10000]==1)/5000),2,2)
colnames(pmat) <- rownames(pmat) <- c(0,1)
print(pmat)
##        0      1
## 0 0.7802 0.2198
## 1 0.2786 0.7214

This means that given that we start in state 0 we have approximately 22% chance of ending in state 1. This would be tedious and annoying to have to do for every length of branch in a tree and fortunately is not necessary. Instead we can matrix exponentiation to calculate the probability matrix for any branch length needed.

# we will use the package ape which includes a matrix exponentiation function
library(ape)
matexpo(qmat*1)
##           [,1]      [,2]
## [1,] 0.7842508 0.2157492
## [2,] 0.2876655 0.7123345

Here we see that although the Monte Carlo simulation approach is laborious it does indeed produce very similar results to the solution provided by matrix exponentiation.

Calculating the likelihood of data on a tree

Lets build a tree to use as an example for the remainder of this project.

phy <- read.tree(text = "(((1:1,2:1):3,(3:2,4:2):2):1,5:5);")
states <- c(0, 0, 0, 1, 1)
names(states) <- 1:5
plot(phy, main="Tree with nodes (black) and tip states (red)")
tiplabels(states,frame="none",adj=-1.5,col="red")
nodelabels(frame="none",adj=-1)

As a first step in calculating the probability of our data lets assign the probabilities of our data at the tips of our tree. We can think of this as the probability of observing our tips if we were to go back and record the phenotype for each of our species a second time. For today’s purposes we are assuming that we know the state of each species with no uncertainty. However, this approach allows us to assign whatever probability we believe appropriate for each tip state allowing us to easily incorporate various types of uncertainty. The boxes that we have added show the probability of either state 0 (left) or state 1 (right).

Now we will go through our tree and for each node where both daughter branches lead to tips we will calculate the probability of the data at the tip assuming that the node was in state 0 and in state 1. So for the first branch at the bottom of the tree we need to solve \(P_{01}(1)\) and \(P_{11}(1)\) the 1 in parentheses is the branch length of the branch.

So we do this with our matrix exponentiation:

pmat1 <- matexpo(qmat*1)
colnames(pmat1) <- rownames(pmat1) <- c(0,1)
pmat1
##           0         1
## 0 0.7842508 0.2157492
## 1 0.2876655 0.7123345

Pulling out the appropriate probabilities we can add another box to our tree:

The next branch up is identical. However the following two branches have branch lengths of 2 each so we will have to make a new P-matrix for them.

pmat2 <- matexpo(qmat*2)
colnames(pmat2) <- rownames(pmat2) <- c(0,1)
pmat2
##          0        1
## 0 0.677113 0.322887
## 1 0.430516 0.569484

Now lets fill in these 3 new boxes on our tree

This brings us to a point where we no longer have any node where both daughter branches are tips. So our next step is to combine the bottom two boxes with one another to set up a pair of probabilities just before the node indicated in red below. Since the evolution in any branch is independent of all other branches we will combine these by multiplication

Next we repeat this process for the node indicated in green:

Conceptually we are now in a similar position as we were at the beginning, but we now have a tree with three tips (the tip at the top plus the green and red node). So now we simply work our way down the tree till we have a single box at the root of the tree.

So now we have to decide how to sum over the two probabilities at the bottom of the tree into a single likelihood for the data given our Q-matrix, tree, and observed species. There are a number of ways to do this we could simply take the average of these giving each equal weight. Or we could weight them by the stationary distribution. Here we will use an approach developed by Rich Fitzjohn that is presented appendix 1 of this 2009 paper. Here we treat the root state as a nuisance parameter and weight the probabilities by how well they explain the data. In our case this yields the following equation for the final likelihood:

\(-\log(0.038\frac{0.038}{.038+.038}+0.038\frac{0.038}{.038+.038})=3.27\)

Now we can compare this to a known good implementation such as from diversitree.

pars <- c(0.3, 0.4)
lnL <- diversitree::make.mk2(phy, states)
-lnL(pars)
## [1] 3.268878

The slight difference that we see is due to the effects of rounding at the base of the tree; without rounding we find that:

probability of data given state 0 = 0.03805276

probability of data given state 1 = 0.03804541

If we use these probabilities then we find that:

# weighted probability of data given state 0
state0 <- 0.03805276 * (0.03805276 / (0.03805276 + 0.03804541))
# weighted probability of data given state 1
state1 <- 0.03804541 * (0.03804541 / (0.03805276 + 0.03804541))
# sum and return the -ln
-log(state0 + state1)
## [1] 3.268878

Maddison and Fitzjohn 2015 [1]

In my opinion this is one of those kind of instantly important papers. It doesn’t present anything that I feel was terribly surprising but it is well written and for those that are just beginning to get into comparative methods I think it is a good paper to make you appropriately paranoid and suspect of significant results arising from a lot of the methods that we employ commonly. I also like this paper because for me it does a great job of why you should visually explore your data. They first show possible outcomes that we can all agree more less should and should not produce significant results for tests of correlation. Below is a screen shot of their figure 1:

So A and B are examples that are clearly suggestive of an interesting pattern and the type of thing that we would want our methods to flag as possibly being significant. However, we can see that C shouldn’t be considered a correlation these two traits could have evolved with out any reciprocal effects and simply inherited by all of the descendants due to shared inheritance. Finally, example D what they call an unreplicated burst is also not a situation where we should find significance. Any trait that evolved on the first black branch of the tree on the left would show a strong correlation with the trait on the right so in this case we likely have a very strong bias due to our choice of characters.

Next they present the results of simulation studies that show that Pagel 1994 [2] approach will return many significant results for both structures like C and D. In fact all simulations of Darwin’s scenario (C) result in highly significant results using Pagel’s test. The authors briefly mention Felsenstein’s phylogenetic extension [3] of Sewell Wright’s threshold model [4] for discrete traits. I find it odd that they didn’t test this method. I haven’t played with it much but it seems that it fits the bill in that it would correctly account for true sample size and should not be led astray the way that these other methods are.

The problem here is pseudoreplication. The amount of shared branch length largely determines the significance of the result based on Maddison’s, Pagel’s and Huelsenbeck’s approaches rather than the number of independent occurences. Also cant write about this article without mentioing the final section where Maddison and Fitzjohn launch into nearly a full page analogy between space time and phylogenies - - Its just awesome.

So where do we go from here… well a quick first thing to do would be to run felsensteins approach on this data and just see does it work better? And this brings me to my one complaint about this article the simulated datasets nor the code that generated them seems to be available…. not sure why that is. So many easy ways to make data/code available these days.
